<p><b>How do I start a career in aircraft maintenance?</b> Minimum Requirements You must have graduated from an FAA Approved Maintenance Technical School. This requirement can be substituted for either 18 months practical work experience with airframes or powerplants, or 30 months practical work experience with both systems simultaneously.</p>
<p><b>How long does it take to become an Ame?</b> 1. **Education**: Most AMEs begin with a post-secondary education program in aircraft maintenance or a related field. These programs can range from 18 months to 2 years for a diploma or associate degree. Some countries may offer longer, more comprehensive programs.</p>
<p><b>Which subject is best for aircraft engineering?</b> Aeronautical is: Applicant must pass 10+2 with Physics, Chemistry, and Mathematics or equivalent. Students having any other optional subject in place of Chemistry are also eligible. E.g. Computer Science in place of chemistry along with Physics and Mathematics.</p>